solution: class Solution {
    public long repairCars(int[] ranks, int cars) {
        long left = 1, right = 1L * ranks[0] * cars * cars;
        for (int r : ranks) right = Math.max(right, 1L * r * cars * cars);

        while (left < right) {
            long mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
            long total = 0;
            for (int r : ranks) {
                total += (long) Math.sqrt(mid / r);
                if (total >= cars) break;
            }
            if (total >= cars) right = mid;
            else left = mid + 1;
        }
        return left;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n log(max(r) * cars^2))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Binary search on the minimum time. For each candidate time, compute how many cars each mechanic can finish (sqrt(time/rank)) and sum them. If the sum is at least cars, the time is feasible. The search space is bounded by the worst-case single-mechanic scenario.

